 {"id":"bd-2l8","title":"Integrate stats collection into server request handling","description":"## Purpose and Rationale

Wire ServerStats collection into FastMCP's request handling pipeline so metrics are automatically captured for every request. This makes the beautiful stats display actually reflect real server activity.

## Background

The ServerStats struct collects metrics, but it needs to be integrated into the actual request flow. Every JSON-RPC request processed by the server should contribute to the statistics. This integration must be non-intrusive and zero-cost when stats are disabled.

## Technical Specification

### Integration Points

#### 1. Server-Level Stats Instance

```rust
// crates/fastmcp/src/server.rs

pub struct Server {
    // Existing fields...

    /// Runtime statistics collector
    stats: Option<ServerStats>,
}

impl Server {
    pub fn new(name: &str) -> Self {
        Self {
            // ...
            stats: Some(ServerStats::new()),
        }
    }

    /// Disable statistics collection
    pub fn without_stats(mut self) -> Self {
        self.stats = None;
        self
    }

    /// Get stats snapshot
    pub fn stats(&self) -> Option<StatsSnapshot> {
        self.stats.as_ref().map(|s| s.snapshot())
    }
}
```

#### 2. Request Handler Instrumentation

```rust
// In request handling path

impl Server {
    async fn handle_request(&self, request: JsonRpcRequest) -> JsonRpcResponse {
        let start = Instant::now();
        let method = request.method.clone();

        // Execute the actual handler
        let result = self.dispatch_request(request).await;

        // Record statistics
        if let Some(stats) = &self.stats {
            let latency = start.elapsed();
            let success = match &result {
                Ok(_) => true,
                Err(_) => false,
            };
            stats.record_request(&method, latency, success);
        }

        result
    }
}
```

#### 3. Connection Tracking

```rust
// In connection management

impl Server {
    async fn handle_connection(&self, stream: impl AsyncRead + AsyncWrite) {
        // Track connection open
        if let Some(stats) = &self.stats {
            stats.connection_opened();
        }

        // Handle requests...
        self.process_messages(stream).await;

        // Track connection close
        if let Some(stats) = &self.stats {
            stats.connection_closed();
        }
    }
}
```

#### 4. Data Transfer Tracking

```rust
// In transport layer

fn record_bytes_received(&self, bytes: usize) {
    if let Some(stats) = &self.stats {
        stats.record_bytes_received(bytes as u64);
    }
}

fn record_bytes_sent(&self, bytes: usize) {
    if let Some(stats) = &self.stats {
        stats.record_bytes_sent(bytes as u64);
    }
}
```

### Stats Display Hook

Add a method to display stats on demand (e.g., on SIGUSR1 or via a special method):

```rust
impl Server {
    /// Display current statistics to stderr
    pub fn display_stats(&self) {
        if let Some(stats) = &self.stats {
            let snapshot = stats.snapshot();
            let renderer = StatsRenderer::new(
                self.theme.clone(),
                self.context.clone()
            );
            renderer.render_panel(&snapshot, &self.console);
        }
    }
}
```

### Periodic Stats Logging

Optionally log stats periodically:

```rust
impl Server {
    fn spawn_stats_logger(&self, interval: Duration) {
        let stats = self.stats.clone();
        let context = self.context.clone();

        asupersync::spawn(async move {
            let mut ticker = asupersync::time::interval(interval);
            loop {
                ticker.tick().await;
                if let Some(ref stats) = stats {
                    let snap = stats.snapshot();
                    tracing::info\!(
                        total_requests = snap.total_requests,
                        success_rate = %format\!("{:.1}%", 
                            snap.successful_requests as f64 / snap.total_requests.max(1) as f64 * 100.0),
                        avg_latency_ms = snap.avg_latency.as_millis(),
                        "Server statistics"
                    );
                }
            }
        });
    }
}
```

